 ### Adapters, bridge, and FFI additions
 
 - The token exchange/refresh/revoke transport is a **distinct component from the
     1	<!--
     2	This Source Code Form is subject to the terms of the Mozilla Public License,
     3	v. 2.0. If a copy of the MPL was not distributed with this file, You can obtain
     4	one at https://mozilla.org/MPL/2.0/.
     5	-->
     6	
     7	# ADR 0023: Step 3 — production OAuth and bounded Gmail sync
     8	
     9	- Status: Accepted
    10	- Date: 2026-07-20
    11	
    12	## Context
    13	
    14	Phase 1 is macOS-first. Step 2 (the macOS UI vertical slice,
    15	[ADR 0021](adr-0021-macos-ui-vertical-slice.md), PRs 2a–2f) shipped native
    16	AppKit/SwiftUI account-connection, inbox, thread, search, and a composer-entry
    17	screen. Those screens read an encrypted SQLCipher store that is **empty**: Step 2
    18	explicitly shipped zero write surface and forbade invoking the OAuth symbols. Step
    19	3 fills the store, so the existing read UI renders real mail, by connecting one
    20	Google account per user and synchronizing a bounded recent mailbox read-only.
    21	
    22	Much of the machinery exists and is reviewed:
    23	
    24	- the PKCE authorization state machine and callback validation
    25	  (`crates/application/src/oauth.rs`);
    26	- the macOS loopback transport and the `tersa_oauth_macos_begin/poll/cancel`
    27	  C ABI, already in the canonical (whitespace-normalized) pinned header and export
    28	  fixtures;
    29	- the Swift session driver `apple/macos/OAuthAuthorizationSession.swift`,
    30	  instantiated and wrapped in a dormant `AppDelegate` method that is not reachable
    31	  from any launch or UI path;
    32	- the official Gmail read adapter ([ADR 0016](adr-0016-gmail-rest-adapter.md),
    33	  `adapters/gmail-rest-macos`), `AccountId`-bound, `Zeroizing` tokens, GET-only
    34	  under a fixed base;
    35	- the bounded sync coordinator ([ADR 0018](adr-0018-bounded-sync-and-cache.md),
    36	  `crates/application/src/sync.rs`) and the store reconcile path.
    37	
    38	The one genuinely new and security-critical subsystem is the **token lifecycle**.
    39	Today the bridge validates the authorization callback and then `drop(grant)`s it
    40	(`apple/rust-bridge/src/oauth.rs`, `complete_callback`): no token exchange, no
    41	refresh, no persistence, no revocation exists anywhere, and
    42	`adapters/keychain-macos` has no token surface. This ADR plans Step 3; it
    43	implements nothing. It follows the ADR 0021 precedent of a plan-only ADR whose
    44	decisions are realized in later, independently reviewed pull requests.
    45	
    46	The binding constraints (unchanged): each user connects **their own** Google
    47	account through the official API; the product application is the sole profile
    48	owner and migration authority; any CLI stays retrieval-only; there is no
    49	write/send to Gmail in Phase 1; performance is the primary constraint
    50	([ADR 0022](adr-0022-performance-primary-constraint.md)); signed distribution and
    51	Developer-ID work stay last (the PR33b credential block).
    52	
    53	## Decision
    54	
    55	### Scope and the Step 3 / Step 4 boundary
    56	
    57	Step 3 delivers: real per-user OAuth sign-in wired to the account-connection UI;
    58	secure token lifecycle; a bounded read-only Gmail fetch that normalizes and writes
    59	recent mail into the encrypted store through the reviewed write path; and the
    60	existing inbox/thread/search rendering that real data. Per-slice size and the
    61	runtime measurements enabled by a populated store are recorded on each PR's
    62	ADR 0022 checklist, but the dedicated performance harness and its thresholds
    63	remain **Step 4**; Step 3 does not build that harness or assert a threshold.
    64	
    65	### Client-secret posture (amends an M0 invariant, empirically resolved)
    66	
    67	The evidenced macOS transport binds an ephemeral `http://127.0.0.1:{port}/`
    68	loopback; only Google's **Desktop app** client type accepts unregistered loopback
    69	redirects. Whether the token endpoint requires the Desktop client's `client_secret`
    70	under PKCE is contested — Google's native-app guidance has described it as optional,
    71	while Desktop clients have historically been issued a secret and rejected exchanges
    72	without it. This ADR does not settle it by reading docs: a one-off `curl` probe of
    73	the token endpoint with the real Desktop client (a 3f prerequisite, run **before**
    74	3a freezes its request shape) determines it empirically. Either result yields the
    75	same posture: if a secret is required it is the Desktop client's, which is **not
    76	confidential** for an installed app (RFC 8252 §8.5); if none is required, none is
    77	sent. This ADR therefore amends the
    78	[OAuth/PKCE feasibility](../m0/oauth-pkce-feasibility.md) deferred-work invariant
    79	"exchange the validated code **without a client secret**" to "without a
    80	**confidential** secret", so the plan holds under either outcome: any secret sent is
    81	a build-injected non-confidential value carried alongside the client ID and used
    82	only at the token endpoint. The alternative — an iOS-type client with no secret —
    83	would force a reversed-client-ID custom-scheme redirect and discard the reviewed
    84	loopback transport, and is rejected. No other feasibility invariant is weakened.
    85	
    86	### Token lifecycle and ownership
    87	
    88	- The **refresh token** is the only persisted credential: a single Keychain item
    89	  per canonical `AccountId`, in the existing access group, with
    90	  `WhenUnlockedThisDeviceOnly` accessibility (stricter than the root key and
    91	  sufficient, since sync is user-triggered with no background work); never written
    92	  to SQLCipher, never crossed over the C ABI, never logged. The store is the 3c
    93	  `RefreshTokenStore` in `tersa-keychain-macos`; the trusted composition that loads
    94	  and rotates it is the dedicated `tersa-oauth-sync-macos` crate (see Sync
    95	  composition, amended 2026-07-21).
    96	- **Rotation is an atomic in-place replace.** Google may return a new refresh token
    97	  on refresh or re-consent. A refresh-token item has one fixed Keychain primary key
    98	  (service + `AccountId` + access group), so a second `SecItemAdd` returns
    99	  `errSecDuplicateItem` and there is no rename: the only atomic replace primitive is
   100	  `SecItemUpdate`, which rotates the stored value in place with no window in which the
   101	  account has no persisted credential (never delete-then-add). ADR 0019 made the
   102	  Keychain surface add-only and deletion-forbidden specifically to keep the
   103	  installation **root key** immutable and non-rotatable; the refresh token is a
   104	  distinct item with a distinct lifecycle that is *designed* to rotate and to be
   105	  withdrawn, so 3c amends the guard with a **token-item-specific** rule —
   106	  `SecItemAdd` for the first store, `SecItemUpdate` for atomic rotation,
   107	  `SecItemDelete` on disconnect and on `invalid_grant` — while the root key stays
   108	  add-only, update- and deletion-forbidden.
   109	- The **access token** stays in memory as a `Zeroizing` value (already
   110	  adapter-side) and is never persisted. Refresh is **proactive**: the composition
   111	  refreshes when the cached access token is within a clock-skew margin of its
   112	  `expires_in` before driving a fetch. Reactive-refresh-on-401 is *not* used — the
   113	  reviewed Gmail adapter (ADR 0016) fails a page on any non-404 error and cannot
   114	  cleanly signal auth expiry — so expiry is tracked from `expires_in`, not inferred
   115	  from a response.
   116	- Refresh is **serialized per account**. Token exchange and refresh are modeled as
   117	  a portable, I/O-free state machine (ports + fakes) with the network transport
   118	  behind an adapter.
   119	- **Refresh failure / revoked consent** (the common path: External + Testing
   120	  expires the refresh token roughly weekly) is a first-class defined transition, not
   121	  an error: an `invalid_grant` or a revoked token deletes the stored refresh token
   122	  and surfaces a **re-connect** UI state; the encrypted store is **preserved** (no
   123	  wipe — the read UI keeps working on cached mail) and the condition is never
   124	  presented as store corruption. Preservation is **conditional on same-account
   125	  re-consent** (see Account-identity gate): if the user re-consents with a different
   126	  Google account, the preserved store would otherwise merge two accounts' mail under
   127	  the one `default` slot, so the identity gate clears it before the first sync write.
   128	- **Disconnect withdraws both consent and the harvested data.** Disconnecting an
   129	  account calls the token `/revoke` endpoint, deletes the Keychain item, **and
   130	  clears that `AccountId`'s cached mailbox from the store through the owning writer**
   131	  in a single account-scoped transaction — revoking consent while leaving the fetched
   132	  mail readable would not be a complete consent story. Step 3 ships the disconnect
   133	  affordance.
   134	- **Account-identity gate.** Because Phase 1 uses a single fixed `default`
   135	  `AccountId` (see Identity binding), the store is guarded so two accounts' mail can
   136	  never coexist under it — on **every** path that reaches a sync write, not only
   137	  explicit disconnect. On the first successful connect the composition records a
   138	  salted hash of the account's immutable OIDC `sub` (in hand from the `id_token` of
   139	  each token response — no network fetch, no identity *displayed*, only a
   140	  per-installation-salted hash stored in the encrypted store). Before any later sync
   141	  write — a fresh connect or a re-connect after refresh failure — it hashes the
   142	  connected account's `sub` and compares: a match preserves the store, a mismatch
   143	  clears the previous account's cached mailbox before the new sync writes and
   144	  records the new hash. The gate is **fail-closed** — if the hasher or the store
   145	  read fails, the sync write is blocked rather than falling through to
   146	  preserve-and-write — and the mailbox clear and the new-hash record commit in one
   147	  account-scoped transaction. This makes the "never coexist" invariant hold for the
   148	  account-switch, fresh-connect, and re-connect paths uniformly. Storing only a
   149	  salted hash (not the subject) keeps this consistent with Identity binding, which
   150	  forbids *displaying* an identity, not gating data lifecycle on a local hash.
   151	  (3d-3a implemented the `sub` keying; see Identity source below for why the mutable
   152	  `emailAddress` it originally used was replaced.)
   153	- **Identity source — `sub` is a 3f-blocking requirement (amended 2026-07-21).**
   154	  The gate as first built (3d-2a) hashes `getProfile.emailAddress`, but an email
   155	  address is **not** an immutable Google-account identifier: Google documents it as
   156	  mutable and reusable, and Workspace permits reassigning a removed address to a new
   157	  account. Under `emailAddress`, that reassignment produces a silent false *match*
   158	  that merges two principals' mail — precisely the outcome this gate exists to
   159	  exclude. The gate is therefore **required to key on the OIDC `sub`** (unique, never
   160	  reused) before the 3f live run; this is a **merge-blocking gate on 3f**, not a
   161	  Phase-1 mechanism change. The gate mechanism is identifier-agnostic — it hashes an
   162	  opaque string and stores only the salted hash — so the swap is confined to adding
   163	  the `openid` scope, reading `sub` from **every** token response's `id_token`
   164	  (exchange **and** refresh — a periodic refresh-driven sync after a restart holds no
   165	  in-memory `sub`, so it must be re-derived from the refresh response), and having the
   166	  connected session implement the profile port from its held `sub`; the salted-hash
   167	  store, the decision logic, and the fail-closed/atomic-clear guarantees are
   168	  unchanged. (Source: the 3d-2a independent review — a confirmed critical — and the
   169	  Fable judgement verdict.)
   170	  - **`id_token` decode is signature-unverified, by design (3d-2b).** The `id_token`
   171	    is only ever read from the token-endpoint response body, received over the token
   172	    transport's hardened TLS client directly from the token endpoint — never from a
   173	    front channel. The TLS origin authenticates the issuer, so its signature is not
   174	    verified (OIDC Core 3.1.3.7). This TLS-back-channel precondition is load-bearing:
   175	    the decode helper is private to the token transport, and the `aud == client_id`
   176	    check (with `iss` restricted to the Google issuers and a non-empty bounded `sub`)
   177	    is what makes the decode-only posture sound. The day an `id_token` is accepted
   178	    from any non-back-channel source, signature verification becomes mandatory.
   179	  - **What 3d-2b landed:** the `openid` scope, the transport-confined `id_token`
   180	    decode, semantic `aud`/`iss`/`sub` validation surfacing a validated subject on
   181	    the token response, and the generic token-lifecycle composition (connect / refresh
   182	    / proactive-refresh). A subject-less token response fails as a **non-destructive**
   183	    `IdentityUnverified` (the stored refresh token is retained for retry), never the
   184	    destructive consent-revoked terminal. 3d-2b makes the `sub` available; wiring it
   185	    to the gate (the port rename, retiring the `emailAddress` GET, and the HKDF
   186	    domain-label/version bump) lands with the concrete session in 3d-3.
   187	  - **`exp`/`iat` validation — a 3d-3-blocking gate (amended 2026-07-21).** 3d-2b
   188	    deliberately does NOT validate the `id_token`'s `exp`/`iat`: the token is always
   189	    freshly minted over the confined TLS back channel (so `exp` is always in the
   190	    future) AND the `sub` reaches no consumer in this slice, so the check would be
   191	    inert twice over, and validating a Unix-time claim needs a wall clock the pure
   192	    token layer deliberately excludes (it keeps `MonotonicClock` only). 3d-3 MUST,
   193	    as a merge-blocking acceptance criterion, validate the claims **in the concrete
   194	    session, before the subject feeds the identity gate, on EVERY token response
   195	    (exchange and refresh)** using a **wall clock (Unix time) owned by the
   196	    session/composition** — no wall-clock port is threaded into the pure token
   197	    layer. Required checks: `exp` present and `now < exp + skew`; `iat` present and
   198	    `iat <= now + skew` (reject a future-minted token); one fixed skew constant
   199	    ≤ 5 minutes. Failure is the existing **non-destructive** `IdentityUnverified`
   200	    (refresh token retained), never consent-revoked. TRIPWIRE (restated): the moment
   201	    any non-back-channel `id_token` source is introduced, **signature verification
   202	    AND `exp`/`iat`/`nonce` validation become mandatory at the acceptance point** —
   203	    no deferral. (Source: the 3d-2b independent review — a Sol confirmed finding —
   204	    and the Fable judgement verdict.)
   205	    - **3d-3a landed** the freshness check at `GmailSession::new` (validated against
   206	      a `WallClock`, 2-minute skew, non-destructive on failure). Because the session
   207	      validates freshness ONCE at construction, the **3d-3c sync worker MUST build a
   208	      fresh `GmailSession` per connect/refresh cycle** and never hold one long-term.
   209	      (Source: the 3d-3a review.)
   210	
   211	### Read-only enforcement
   212	
   213	Two server/build-enforced boundaries plus one source-convention layer, defense in
   214	depth:
   215	
   216	1. The genuinely enforced boundary is the Google-side scope
   217	   `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly` only (the metadata scope cannot
   218	   fetch bodies; a modify/write scope is forbidden). 3a must **replace** the current
   219	   `GMAIL_MODIFY_SCOPE` constant, not add a read-only one beside it, so no code path
   220	   can still request `gmail.modify`; `access_type=offline` (already present,
   221	   required for the refresh token) is retained.
   222	2. No write/send symbol exists in the exported C ABI allowlist (xtask-enforced) —
   223	   also structural.
   224	3. The adapter is GET-only under the fixed Gmail base (ADR 0016) — a source
   225	   convention reinforcing the two boundaries above, not itself a compile boundary.
   226	
   227	The CLI reachability caveat extends to the token surface: the `xtask` source
   228	allowlist must explicitly deny any CLI-reachable path to the token, exchange,
   229	refresh, or revoke entries — defense in depth atop the compile boundary.
   230	
   231	### Sync composition and write-path authority
   232	
   233	Sync writes run **only** through the new trusted `tersa-oauth-sync-macos`
   234	composition crate — a dedicated crate, not an entry in `tersa-keychain-macos`
   235	(amended 2026-07-21): giving `tersa-keychain-macos` the `tersa-gmail-rest-macos` /
   236	`tokio` edges would make everything that depends on it — including the
   237	**retrieval-only CLI** — transitively link `reqwest` (network), permanently deleting
   238	the machine-checked reqwest-exclusivity that expresses the CLI's retrieval-only,
   239	zero-network invariant. The composition crate keeps `tersa-keychain-macos` (the token
   240	store) and the CLI off the network graph, realizing the dedicated-composition-crate
   241	refactor the Consequences section anticipates. It loads the refresh token, refreshes
   242	proactively, drives the existing `GmailMailbox` fetch and `SyncCoordinator` bounded
   243	recent sync, and reconciles into the store over the existing **validated read-write**
   244	SQLCipher path. The store remains the sole writer and migration authority; the sync
   245	entry is an authorized
   246	caller, not a second authority.
   247	
   248	Concurrency: the store runs persistent WAL — one writer, many readers. Step 3 adds
   249	a second read-write open (sync reconcile) alongside the bootstrap read-write open
   250	and the ADR 0021 read-only UI readers. ADR 0019 scoped the global bootstrap lock to
   251	"serialize cooperative bootstraps"; this ADR **amends** that contract to widen it to
   252	serialize **every** read-write store open — bootstrap and sync alike — so a single
   253	owning writer holds it at a time; WAL leaves the read-only UI readers unaffected.
   254	The lock guards only the store-open-plus-reconcile-write critical section and is
   255	**never held across network I/O**: bounded message bodies are fetched (per ADR 0018)
   256	*before* the lock is taken and written under it in one short transaction, so a
   257	network stall can never hold the writer. Sync stays bounded and single-flight per
   258	ADR 0018 (only one sync runs at a time regardless of the lock); sync status crossing
   259	the bridge is a closed integer set with no addresses, subjects, or per-person mail
   260	counts beyond ADR 0018's aggregate.
   261	
   262	The identity gate and the sync write it guards are distinct steps, so the
   263	**whole gate-to-write cycle** must be serialized per account slot, not just each
   264	transaction — otherwise two overlapping cycles could interleave a stale
   265	identity record over a committed one and let two accounts' mail coexist. The 3d-2a
   266	`gated_sync` building block documents this precondition but does not enforce it;
   267	enforcement is a **3d-3 acceptance criterion with two parts (amended 2026-07-21)**:
   268	(1) the Rust-owned sync worker is the **sole** production caller and holds one
   269	whole-cycle permit per account slot — a concurrent begin returns busy rather than
   270	queuing a second cycle; and (2) an **in-transaction identity fence** — the sync
   271	carries the cycle's fresh identity hash and every mailbox-write transaction commits
   272	only if the slot's recorded hash still equals it, aborting on mismatch. The permit
   273	is convention; the in-transaction fence is the guarantee, holding even cross-process
   274	or under a future caller that ignores the worker discipline. (Source: the 3d-2a
   275	independent review — a confirmed critical — and the Fable judgement verdict.)
   276	
   277	  - **3d-3b landed part (2), the fence (amended 2026-07-21).** `run_identity_gate`
   278	    now returns the identity hash it committed (on `Match`, the hash it just
   279	    verified) as the cycle's fence; `gated_sync` threads it into `sync_recent`, and
   280	    `MailboxStore::reconcile_recent_envelopes` / `cache_message_if_present` both take
